<p id="p0048">To address these aspects, we extend the initial problem formulation as follows. The set of laboratories is partitioned as 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M41" altimg="si43.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>L</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo>
    <msub>
     <mi>L</mi>
     <mn>1</mn>
    </msub>
    <mo>∪</mo>
    <mo>…</mo>
    <mo>∪</mo>
    <msub>
     <mi>L</mi>
     <mi>n</mi>
    </msub>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (with 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M42" altimg="si44.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mi>L</mi>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>∩</mo>
    <msub>
     <mi>L</mi>
     <mi>j</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mo>
    <mi>∅</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> for any two 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M43" altimg="si45.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>i</mi>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mi>j</mi>
    <mo>∈</mo>
    <mo>{</mo>
    <mn>1</mn>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mo>…</mo>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mi>n</mi>
    <mo>}</mo>
    <mo>,</mo>
    <mspace width="0.28em"/>
    <mi>i</mi>
    <mo>≠</mo>
    <mi>j</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>). We call each set composing the partition a 
 <italic>region</italic>.
</p>
